Nuphar advena

   [8001.jpg]
   Authority (Ait.) Ait. f.
   Family
   Synonyms Nuphar lutea ssp advena
   Common names European yellow pond-lily, pond-lily, yellow pond-lily,
   spatterdock, cow lily, yellow cow lily, yellow pondlily, yellow water
   lily, brandy bottle
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 8001

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: It is a perennial, aquatic, herbaceous plant spreading for
   up to 2.5 m or more the water surface. It has large, spongy and
   extensively creeping rhizomes and large heart-shaped leaves reaching
   35-40 cm in length and 20-25 cm in width, usually with wavy margins.
   Flowers are yellow, cup-shaped at or above the water surface, 5-7 cm in
   diameter. USE: The seeds are edible, being ground up and used as
   thickeners in soups, made into bread or were parched and eaten as
   popcorn, etc. The rhizome can be boiled or roasted with fowl or other
   game. Leaves and roots have medicinal properties and the plant is grown
   as an ornamental. GROWING PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: Cow lily,
   Yellow cow lily, Yellow pondlily. FURTHER INF: It occurs in ponds,
   ditches, muddy lakes and slow flowing streams usually in shallow water
   but can also be found at depth to 2 m and can grow in tidal water. It
   can be found in eastern North America from Canada to Mexico, reaching
   Cuba and in Japan, and Europe.

   Sources
   http://aquat1.ifas.ufl.edu/nulupic.html
   http://www.botany.com/nuphar.html
   http://www.ibiblio.org/herbmed/eclectic/kings/nymphaea.html

